The '''Korean War''' (South Korean {{Korean|hangul=6.25 전쟁, 한국전쟁|hanja=6.25 戰爭, 韓國戰爭|rr=Yugio Jeonjaeng, Hanguk Jeonjaeng|mr=}}, lit. "6/25 War" or "Korean War"; North Korean {{Korean|hangul=조국해방전쟁|hanja=祖國解放戰爭|mr=Choguk haebang chŏnjaeng|context=north}}, "[[Fatherland]] Liberation War"; 25 June 1950{{Nbsp}}–{{Nbsp}}27 July 1953)<ref name="US neutral commission" /><ref name="NK state of war">{{cite news|title=North Korea enters 'state of war' with South |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-21979127 |access-date=30 March 2013 |newspaper=BBC News |date=30 March 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330013512/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-21979127 |archive-date=30 March 2013 }}</ref>{{refn |name=nbArmistice Agreement |group=lower-alpha | As per armistice agreement of 1953, the opposing sides had to "insure a complete cessation of hostilities and of all acts of armed force in Korea until a final peaceful settlement is achieved".<ref name="Armistice Agreement" />}} was a [[war]] between [[North Korea]] (with military support from [[China]] and the [[Soviet Union]]) and [[South Korea]] (backed by [[Military personnel|personnel]] from the [[United Nations]], principally the [[United States]]). The war began on 25 June 1950 when North Korea invaded South Korea following clashes along the border and [[insurrections]] in the south.<ref>"The creation of an independent South Korea became UN policy in early 1948. Southern communists opposed this, and by autumn partisan warfare had engulfed parts of every Korean province below the 38th parallel. The fighting expanded into a limited border war between the South's newly formed Republic of Korea Army (ROKA) and the North Korean border constabulary as well as the North's Korean People's Army (KPA)."{{cite web|last1=Millett (PHD) |first1=Allan |title=Korean War |url=http://www.britannica.com/event/Korean-War |website=britannica.com |access-date=21 April 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424090911/http://www.britannica.com/event/Korean-War |archive-date=24 April 2016 }}</ref>{{sfn|Cumings|2005|pp=247–53}}{{sfn|Stueck|2002|p=71}} The war ended unofficially on 27 July 1953 in an [[Korean Armistice Agreement|armistice]].

After the [[surrender of Japan]] at the end of [[World War II]] on 15 August (officially 2 September) 1945, the United States and the Soviet Union [[Division of Korea|divided Korea]] along the [[38th parallel north|38th parallel]] into two zones of occupation. The [[Provisional People's Committee of North Korea|Soviets administered the northern zone]] and the [[United States Army Military Government in Korea|Americans administered the southern zone]]. In 1948, as a result of [[Cold War]] tensions, the occupation zones became two [[sovereign states]]. A [[capitalist state]], the [[First Republic of Korea]], was established in the south under the [[First Republic of Korea|authoritarian leadership]] of [[Syngman Rhee]], and a [[socialist state]], the [[Democratic People's Republic of Korea]] was established in the north under the [[Politics of North Korea|totalitarian leadership]] of [[Kim Il-sung]]. Both governments of the two new Korean states claimed to be the sole legitimate government of all of [[Korea]], and neither accepted the border as permanent.

North Korean [[Korean People's Army]] (KPA) forces crossed the border and drove into South Korea on 25 June 1950.<ref name="Devine 2007 819-821" /> The [[United Nations Security Council]] denounced the North Korean move as an invasion and authorized the formation of the [[United Nations Command]] and the dispatch of forces to Korea<ref>[[United Nations Security Council Resolution 83]]</ref> to repel it.<ref>[[United Nations Security Council Resolution 82]]</ref><ref>Derek W. Bowett, United Nations Forces: A Legal Study of United Nations Practice, Stevens, London, 1964, pp. 29–60</ref> The [[Soviet Union]] was boycotting the UN for recognising [[Taiwan]] as [[China]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/United-Nations-Security-Council|title=United Nations Security Council - History|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> and China (mainland) was not recognised by the UN, so neither could support their ally North Korea at the Security Council meeting. Twenty-one countries of the United Nations eventually contributed to the UN force, with the United States providing around 90% of the military personnel.<ref>{{cite book|title=Korea: Where the American Century Began|first=Michael|last=Pembroke|publisher=Hardie Grant Books|date=2018|page=141}}</ref>

After the first two months of war, [[Republic of Korea Army|South Korean Army]] (ROKA) and American forces hastily dispatched to Korea were on the point of defeat, retreating to a small area behind a defensive line known as the [[Battle of Pusan Perimeter|Pusan Perimeter]]. In September 1950, a [[Battle of Inchon|risky amphibious UN counteroffensive]] was launched at [[Incheon]], cutting off KPA troops and supply lines in South Korea. Those who escaped envelopment and capture were forced back north. UN forces [[UN offensive into North Korea|invaded North Korea]] in October 1950 and moved rapidly towards the [[Yalu River]]—the border with China—but on 19 October 1950, Chinese forces of the [[People's Volunteer Army]] (PVA) [[UN offensive into North Korea#The Chinese intervene (19 October)|crossed the Yalu and entered the war]].<ref name="Devine 2007 819-821" /> [[UN retreat from North Korea]] after the [[First Phase Offensive]] and the [[Second Phase Offensive]], then Chinese forces were in South Korea by late December.

In these and subsequent battles, [[Seoul]] was [[Battle of Seoul (disambiguation)|captured four times]], and communist forces were [[UN May–June 1951 counteroffensive|pushed back]] to positions around the 38th parallel, close to where the war had started. After this, the front stabilized, and the last two years were a [[attrition warfare|war of attrition]]. The war in the air, however, was never a stalemate. North Korea was subject to a massive US bombing campaign. [[Jet fighters]] confronted each other in [[air-to-air combat]] for the first time in history, and Soviet pilots covertly flew in defense of their communist allies.

The fighting ended on 27 July 1953 when the [[Korean Armistice Agreement]] was signed. The agreement created the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone]] (DMZ) to separate North and South Korea, and allowed the return of prisoners. However, no [[peace treaty]] was ever signed, and the two Koreas are technically still at war, engaged in a [[frozen conflict]].<ref name="HeFeng2013">{{cite book|last1=He |first1=Kai |last2=Feng |first2=Huiyun |title=Prospect Theory and Foreign Policy Analysis in the Asia Pacific: Rational Leaders and Risky Behavior |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iAaHqijyLy8C&pg=PA50 |year=2013 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1135131197 |page=50 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704225317/https://books.google.com/books?id=iAaHqijyLy8C&pg=PA50 |archive-date=4 July 2017 }}</ref><ref name="LiCribb2014">{{cite book|last1=Li |first1=Narangoa |last2=Cribb |first2=Robert |title=Historical Atlas of Northeast Asia, 1590–2010: Korea, Manchuria, Mongolia, Eastern Siberia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zfMYBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA194 |year=2014 |publisher=Columbia University Press |isbn=978-0231160704 |page=194 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704225317/https://books.google.com/books?id=zfMYBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA194 |archive-date=4 July 2017 }}</ref> In April 2018, the leaders of North and South Korea met at the DMZ<ref>{{cite news|title=Kim becomes first North Korean leader to cross border into South since war|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-southkorea-summit-crossing/kim-becomes-first-north-korean-leader-to-cross-border-into-south-since-war-idUSKBN1HY01L|access-date=28 April 2018|work=Reuters|date=27 April 2018}}</ref> and agreed to work toward a treaty to formally end the Korean War.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/north-korea-south-korea-summit-intl/index.html|title=North and South Korean leaders hold historic summit: Live updates|work=CNN|date=26 April 2018|access-date=27 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>

The Korean War was among the most destructive conflicts of the modern era, with [[#Casualties|approximately 3 million war fatalities]] and a larger proportional civilian death toll than [[World War II]] or the [[Vietnam War]]. It incurred the destruction of virtually all of Korea's major cities, [[#Civilian deaths and massacres|thousands of massacres]] by both sides, including the [[Bodo League massacre|mass killing of tens of thousands of suspected communists]] by the South Korean government, and the [[#UN Command POWs|torture and starvation of prisoners of war]] by the North Koreans. North Korea became [[#Bombing of North Korea|among the most heavily bombed countries]] in history.

